    <p>
        This sample sandbox client application demonstrates interacting a simple client application interacting with <a href="http://members.orcid.org/api/oauth">ORCID OAuth2</a> service. For a comprehensive overview visit <a href="http://members.orcid.org/api" target="member_api">http://members.orcid.org/api</a>.
    </p>

    <h4>Two Legged OAuth2 Flow</h4>
    <strong> Leggs  - Client, Server</strong>. Used for getting tokens to access API resources not owned by reseachers.
    In this example we will request a /read-public token which allows access to read and search public ORCID records with 
    the ORCID Member API. Read more <a href="http://members.orcid.org/api/post-oauthtoken-reading-public-data" target="twoStepReadMore">here</a>.
    <p></p>
    <p class="home"><a class="btn btn-default btn-lg" href="/twoStep">Request a /read-public token</a></p>
    <p></p>
    <hr>
    <h4>Three Legged OAuth2 Flow</h4>
    <strong> Leggs - User, Client, Server</strong>. Used for getting tokens to access API resources owned by researchers.
    In this example we will request access to authenticate a users ORCID iD and permission to update their ORCID Activities. 
    <ol>
       <li><strong>User interacts with authorization server</strong>. User is redirected to authorization server with link parameters identifying requesting client application. User approves or denies permission for client access.</li>
       <li><strong>User interacts with client application</strong>. User is redirected to client application with authorization code.</li>
       <li><strong>Client application interacts with authorization server</strong>. Client reads authorization code from URL. Uses authorization code and client secret to exchange authorization code for token allowing access.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
    Learn more <a href="http://members.orcid.org/api/tokens-through-3-legged-oauth-authorization" target="3leggedFlow">here</a>. 
	  </p>
    <p class="home"><a class="btn btn-default btn-lg" href="<%= authorization_uri %>">As a user, visit authorization link</a></p>
    <p class="note"><strong>NOTE:</strong> it's ok to create fake/test accounts on sandbox.</p>
